{
  "text": "The conditions AC(2), P (2) and K(2) have generalisations AC(n), P (n) and K(n) in which the distance d(a, b) is allowed to be at most n instead of at most 2. It is straight-forward to prove that a group is AC(n) for some n \u2265 2 if and only if it is AC(2). (The same cannot be said of P (2) and K [CITATION_1] .) The proof of Theorem 1 can be generalised to show that the bounds also apply to AC(n), P (n) and K(n) groups (n \u2265 2).",
  "citation_candidates": [
